huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
This is a Once in a lifetime hunt. The quality of the bulls on this unit is average. Moose can be found during this hunt anywhere across the unit from the highest elevations in the Wilderness area to the lowest along the Duchesne River corridor. Hunters should be aware of Ute tribal lands and learn the boundaries. Public hunting is not permitted on tribal Lands. There are no CWMUs on this unit.
Moose are found primarily along stream corridors and near lakes and ponds. They can also be found in forested areas and brushy areas away from water.
This unit includes the South Slope portion of the High Uintas Wilderness Area. The wilderness can provide a remote hunt with very few hunters but moose can be hard to locate. Much of the habitat in the high country is fairly sterile without much feed. It is generally Lodge Pole Pine with little understory vegetation. Road access on the remainder of the unit is limited to mostly canyon bottoms due to the steepness of the terrain.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for hot, dry, or rainy, lightening, windy and even snowy conditions.  Early snow storms occur often during this hunt.  Most of the time snow will melt off within a day or so.  Be prepared for muddy or snowy conditions.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Migration Patterns: Moose on this unit can be found almost anywhere during the hunt. This herd generally move down in elevation for the winter. Most of the moose winter on Ute Tribal Lands or on lower elevation slopes on Forest Service lands. They also winter in river bottoms etc... Some moose are found on ridgetops and fairly high elevation during the winter.

Moose rut: The moose rut on this unit usually peaks the end of Sept. and early Oct. The rut is usually dropping off by the end of the hunt. Some hunters are successful calling in bulls during this hunt, but most bulls are harvested simply by spot and stalk style hunting. During the rut, bull moose will cover a lot of ground looking for cows that are in heat. Finding a bull in one canyon does not mean he will still be there the next day when they really get rutty. When on the rut and looking for cows, bulls will often make a low grunting noise while they travel.

Recommended areas in the South Slope, Yellowstone: There are numerous suggested areas to hunt on this unit.
The Wilderness Area can provide a remote hunt with few hunters but is very tough to hunt and it can be hard to locate moose. Much of the habitat in the high country is fairly sterile without much feed. It is generally Lodge Pole Pine with little understory. Moose in the wilderness are generally found near lakes and along the stream corridors.
During the hunt, most of the moose are found near water but can be also be found in brushy or timbered areas.
The suggested areas to hunt include (starting on the west side of the unit):
Mirror Lake Hwy- Hwy 150 is the west boundary of the hunt, closest to the Wasatch front
Soapstone/Iron Mine- good road access, closer to the Wasatch Front
North Fork of the Duchesne- limited road access
Log Hollow- must cross tribal Lands to access, rough roads
Rock Creek- paved road access, steep areas, be aware of tribal boundary
Bear Wallow- steep terrain, be aware of tribal boundary
Lake Fork/Moon Lake- paved road access, some private property to be aware of
Yellowstone- rough roads, be aware of tribal boundary
77 Flat/Burnt Mill- gravel roads, a little flatter area, be aware of tribal boundary
Dry Gulch- very rough road, steep terrain, be aware of tribal boundary on the east
Uinta Canyon- tribal lands down low, steep terrain
Painter Basins- wilderness area, very remote
Elk Horn Loop- gravel roads that go almost to the summit of the Uinta Mountains, lots of opportunity to scatter out, good access to the high country
Whiterocks Canyon- Whiterocks River is the eastern unit boundary, steep terrain

You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: Public lands are all Forest Service lands managed by the Ashley and Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forests.  This unit includes a large portion of the High Uintas Wilderness Area where all motor vehicles are prohibited.  This unit also includes large tracts of Ute tribal lands that are closed to non-tribal members.  The tribal lands are mostly the lower elevation sagebrush zone but in some areas they reach up into the aspen/conifer zone.  There is a large amount of private property on the unit too.  Most of the private property is below the tribal boundary but there are several parcels of private property in the canyon bottoms.
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: Little Montes Creek WMA north of Ballard and Kevin Conway WMA southeast of Myton.  Elk, bear and cougar are rarely found on these WMAs.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the forest. There are special restrictions on camping and campfires in certain areas within the Wilderness area. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Ashley National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/uwcnf
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: The main access points for the High Uintas Wilderness include: Uinta Canyon Trailhead, West Fork of Whiterocks Trailhead, Chepeta Trailhead, Lake Fork Trailhead, Yellowstone/Swift Creek Trailhead, Jackson Park road, Dry Gulch road, Rock Creek Trailhead, North Fork of Duchesne Trailhead, and Grandview trailheads
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS 1:100,000 Kings Peak and Duchesne topo maps
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: All roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service. Maps can also be purchased online at:http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The hunt unit does not include the Ute tribal lands.  There is a large tract of Ute tribal trust land that stretches east to west across the South Slope of the Uinta Mountains.  Road access across the tribal land is permitted only across the main access roads to the Forest.  All ATVs are prohibited on tribal Lands, they must be trailered on access roads across tribal Lands.
